# 🚀 Strings in C

Before today, arrays stored numbers.

Today you'll learn:

👉 How C stores words, names, sentences, and text.

---

# 🧠 Concept 1: What is a String?

## ✅ Definition

A string is a sequence of characters ending with a special character:

```c
'\0'
```

called the **null character**.

Example:

```c
char name[] = "Akshay";
```

---

# 💡 Real-World Analogy

Think of a train 🚆

```text
A  k  s  h  a  y  \0
```

Each character is a coach.

The last coach is:

```text
\0
```

which means:

> "End of the string."

Without it, C won't know where the word ends.

---

# ⚙️ Why Strings Are Special in C

Many languages have a built-in String type.

Example:

```java
String name = "Akshay";
```

In C:

❌ No built-in String type.

Instead:

```c
char name[7] = "Akshay";
```

A string is simply:

> An array of characters.

---

# 🔥 MOST IMPORTANT CONCEPT

When you write:

```c
char name[] = "CAT";
```

C actually stores:

```text
C
A
T
\0
```

Memory:

```text
Index: 0 1 2 3
Value: C A T \0
```

---

# 🧠 Memory Trick

Remember:

**"A string is just a character array with a hidden `\0` at the end."**

---

# 💻 Example

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

    char name[] = "Akshay";

    printf("%s", name);

    return 0;
}
```

Output:

```text
Akshay
```

---

# 🧠 Concept 2: String Input & Output

## ✅ Printing a String

Use:

```c
%s
```

Example:

```c
printf("%s", name);
```

---

## ✅ Taking Input

```c
scanf("%s", name);
```

Example:

```c
char name[20];

scanf("%s", name);
```

---

# ⚠️ Important Limitation

Suppose user enters:

```text
Akshay Gabriel
```

Output stored:

```text
Akshay
```

Only first word gets stored.

Why?

Because:

```c
scanf("%s")
```

stops at space.

---

# 🔥 Better Way: fgets()

```c
fgets(name, sizeof(name), stdin);
```

This can read:

```text
Akshay Gabriel
```

including spaces.

---

# 💡 Real-World Analogy

Think of:

### scanf("%s")

Reading only first name.

### fgets()

Reading full sentence.

---

# 💻 Example

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

    char name[50];

    fgets(name, sizeof(name), stdin);

    printf("%s", name);

    return 0;
}
```

---

# 🔥 Internal Understanding

When you print:

```c
printf("%s", name);
```

C starts at:

```c
name[0]
```

and keeps printing characters until:

```c
'\0'
```

is found.

That's why the null character is so important.

---

# 🧠 Memory Trick

Remember:

**"%s prints until it sees `\0`."**

---

# 🎯 Interview Insight (VERY IMPORTANT)

Common questions:

❓ Does C have a String data type?

Answer:

> No. Strings are character arrays.

---

❓ Why is `\0` needed?

Answer:

> It tells C where the string ends.

---

❓ Difference between `scanf("%s")` and `fgets()`?

Answer:

| scanf("%s")    | fgets()         |
| -------------- | --------------- |
| Stops at space | Reads full line |
| Simpler        | Safer           |

---

